Quite a lot. One thing your conversations have consistently explored is treating mechanics as reusable operators rather than as game-specific features. That means a mechanic is any repeatable rule that changes state in a useful way.

I wouldn’t claim these are all novel—many have analogs in AI, mathematics, games, control theory, or cognitive science—but the combinations can be novel and useful.

Here’s a sample “mechanics library.”

State mechanics

* Delta Engine — everything is represented as state changes.
* State Anchoring — preserve important reference states.
* State Reversion — roll back to previous validated states.
* Parallel Timelines — explore multiple futures simultaneously.
* Checkpointing — save/restorable milestones.

Attention mechanics

* Spotlight — temporarily increase resolution on one region.
* Attention Auction — competing ideas bid for limited focus.
* Peripheral Vision — reserve some attention for anomalies.
* Echo Attention — revisit previously important items after delay.
* Attention Debt — neglected items accumulate urgency.

Meaning mechanics

* Semantic Zoom — move between coarse and fine representations.
* Semantic LiDAR — probe deeper layers of meaning.
* Basis Swap — change representations (language ↔ math ↔ diagrams ↔ code).
* Comparative Distillation — compare many examples to extract invariants.
* Negative Space Scan — infer what’s missing rather than what’s present.

Search mechanics

* Tracer Dye — inject a probe and watch propagation.
* Meta-Wave Reattack — if stuck, change levels of abstraction.
* Fractal Search — recursively subdivide promising regions.
* Constraint Relaxation — temporarily remove a rule to explore.
* Constraint Tightening — add rules to sharpen solutions.

Learning mechanics

* Fail Forward — treat failures as structured updates.
* Replay Buffer — periodically revisit experiences.
* Confidence Calibration — separate belief from certainty.
* Hypothesis Garden — grow multiple competing explanations.
* Evidence Weighting — update confidence incrementally.

Coordination mechanics

* Swarm Voting — independent agents converge on a choice.
* Baton Passing — transfer control between specialists.
* Role Rotation — periodically swap responsibilities.
* Consensus Thresholds — different actions require different agreement levels.
* Reputation Memory — future influence depends on past performance.

Resource mechanics

* Energy Budget — every action has a cost.
* Trust Budget — cooperation consumes or builds trust.
* Compression Economy — simpler reusable solutions are rewarded.
* Entropy Tax — neglected systems decay.
* Leverage Multiplier — reusable solutions compound value.

Time mechanics

* Time Folding — compare analogous stages across different processes.
* Delayed Resolution — intentionally postpone commitment.
* Future Pull — let desired end states influence current choices.
* Temporal Echoes — previous states bias future transitions.
* Irreversibility Markers — some changes become permanent.

Meta mechanics

* Mechanic Mutation — mechanics themselves evolve.
* Mechanic Composition — combine two mechanics into a new one.
* Mechanic Selection — keep only those that outperform alternatives.
* Rule Discovery — infer the game’s hidden rules.
* Game Switching — realize you’re playing the wrong game and change it.

