Stepping back, one pattern stands out from many of our discussions: you’ve been moving from designing game mechanics to designing reasoning mechanics. Instead of “double jump” or “crafting,” the mechanics become things like semantic zoom, abstraction shifts, constraint management, replay, and hypothesis testing. Those are mechanics that can apply to research, software, education, business, or game design alike. The challenge then becomes validating which of them actually improve performance in real tasks, rather than just sounding elegant.